6 EXPERIMENTS :
6-1:5.1 Experiment design Our major hypothesis is that using search context (i.e., query history and clickthrough information) can help improve search accuracy .
6-2:In particular, the search context can provide extra information to help us estimate a better query model than using just the current query .
6-3:So most of our experiments involve comparing the retrieval performance using the current query only (thus ignoring any context) with that using the current query as well as the search context .
6-4:Since we collected four versions of queries for each topic, we make such comparisons for each version of queries .
6-5:We use two performance measures: (1) Mean Average Precision (MAP): This is the standard non interpolated average precision and serves as a good measure of the overall ranking accuracy .
6-6:(2) Precision at 20 documents (pr@20docs): This measure does not average well, but it is more meaningful than MAP and reflects the utility for users who only read the top 20 documents .
6-7:In all cases, the reported figure is the average over all of the 30 topics .
6-8:We evaluate the four models for exploiting search context (i.e., FixInt, BayesInt, OnlineUp, and BatchUp) .
6-9:Each model has precisely two parameters (α and β for FixInt; µ and ν for others) .
6-10:Note that µ and ν may need to be interpreted differently for different methods .
6-11:We vary these parameters and identify the optimal performance for each method .
6-12:We also vary the parameters to study the sensitivity of our algorithms to the setting of the parameters .
6-13:5.2 Result analysis 5.2.1 Overall effect of search context We compare the optimal performances of four models with those using the current query only in Table 1 .
6-14:A row labeled with qi is the baseline performance and a row labeled with qi + HQ + HC is the performance of using search context .
6-15:We can make several observations from this table: reformulated queries are better than the previous queries with the performance of q4 being the best .
6-16:Users generally formulate better and better queries .
6-17:when the context is rich .
6-18:This can be seen from the fact that the 1 http: sifaka.cs.uiuc.edu ir ucair QCHistory.zip improvement for q4 and q3 is generally more substantial compared with q2 .
6-19:Actually, in many cases with q2, using the context may hurt the performance, probably because the history at that point is sparse .
6-20:When the search context is rich, the performance improvement can be quite substantial .
6-21:For example, BatchUp achieves 92.4% improvement in the mean average precision over q3 and 77.2% improvement over q4 .
6-22:(The generally low precisions also make the relative improvement deceptively high, though.) of FixInt and OnlineUp are clearly worse than those of BayesInt and BatchUp .
6-23:Since BayesInt performs better than FixInt and the main difference between BayesInt and FixInt is that the former uses an adaptive coefficient for interpolation, the results suggest that using adaptive coefficient is quite beneficial and a Bayesian style interpolation makes sense .
6-24:The main difference between OnlineUp and BatchUp is that OnlineUp uses decaying coefficients to combine the multiple clicked summaries, while BatchUp simply concatenates all clicked summaries .
6-25:Therefore the fact that BatchUp is consistently better than OnlineUp indicates that the weights for combining the clicked summaries indeed should not be decaying .
6-26:While OnlineUp is theoretically appealing, its performance is inferior to BayesInt and BatchUp, likely because of the decaying coefficient .
6-27:Overall, BatchUp appears to be the best method when we vary the parameter settings .
6-28:We have two different kinds of search context query history and clickthrough data .
6-29:We now look into the contribution of each kind of context .
6-30:5.2.2 Using query history only In each of four models, we can turn off the clickthrough history data by setting parameters appropriately .
6-31:This allows us to evaluate the effect of using query history alone .
6-32:We use the same parameter setting for query history as in Table 1 .
6-33:The results are shown in Table 2 .
6-34:Here we see that in general, the benefit of using query history is very limited with mixed results .
6-35:This is different from what is reported in a previous study [15], where using query history is consistently helpful .
6-36:Another observation is that the context runs perform poorly at q2, but generally perform (slightly) better than the baselines for q3 and q4 .
6-37:This is again likely because at the beginning the initial query, which is the title in the original TREC topic description, may not be a good query; indeed, on average, performances of these first generation queries are clearly poorer than those of all other user formulated queries in the later generations .
6-38:Yet another observation is that when using query history only, the BayesInt model appears to be better than other models .
